Chapter 8 polls: Is Donald Trump for real?
There have been attempts to brand Trump as a nobody.
He has also been seen as a joke.
Some predict a collapse for Trump.
In Republican circles, every effort has been made (so far) without success to drag Trump down from the poll lead.
Ten of the 11 national polls show double-digit approval ratings for Donald Trump. Some are already seriously considering what that actually says about the real estate mogul's candidacy chances.
True, the election is in the early stages.
It has not yet been announced that Trump will be nominated for the Republican nomination.
Experts remind us that at this time in 2011, pollster Rick Perry was allowed to give way to a rising Herman Cain. Neither ultimately won a candidate election in any of the states.
For many reasons, Trump would have a tough time in a general election.
Outside factions such as Jeb Bush's Super PAC as well as the economic conservative group Club for Growth have noted Trump's strong position and begun digging in their doves to topple him.
The following recent polling data shows that the property mogul cannot be dismissed with a shrug:
There has been an about-face in Trump's endorsement.
Just before Trump announced he was running in mid-June, according to a Monmouth University poll, only two in 10 Republicans had a positive image of the real estate mogul.
By mid-July, already 40 percent had a positive image.
At the beginning of August, the corresponding figure was 52 per cent.
Now, six in 10 Republicans have a positive image of Donald Trump.
About three out of ten people have a negative opinion.
Those numbers also hold in states where elections are held first.
At last week's Quinnipiac gallup, 60 percent of Republicans had a favorable view of Trump.
Two-thirds of Republicans would welcome a Trump candidacy.
In a CNN/ORC poll last week, 67 percent of Republicans polled said they were very satisfied or satisfied with Trump's potential pick for the nomination.
Only two in 10 would be highly dissatisfied with Trump's candidacy.
Ben Carson elicits a response almost as enthusiastic as Trump's (43 percent would be very happy with Carson's candidacy and 40 percent with Trump's).
Who is the next most popular candidate?
In third place is Marco Rubio, with a similar 21 percent approval rating.
On the other hand, 47 percent of Republicans would be dissatisfied or very unhappy if Jeb Bush were chosen as the party's nominee.
Most Republicans don't see Trump's temperament as problematic.
Donald Trump has been widely criticized for pomp and offensive comments. Fifty-two percent of Republican supporters nationwide think the real estate mogul's qualities are appropriate for a president. The views are evident from an ABC News/Washington Post poll.
The same reading applies to Iowa, where the convention will be held first: According to the Quinnipiac Gallup, 52 percent of Republicans think Trump's personal qualities are appropriate for a commander-in-chief.
However, according to an ABC/Post poll, 44 percent think Trump is not capable of performing the job effectively, and six in 10 think Trump's temperament is unbecoming of the White House.
Republicans are getting used to the idea.
They're starting to take Trump seriously.
When asked by Republicans who is most likely to be chosen as the party's nominee, according to a CNN/ORC poll, four in 10 believe in Trump's chances.
That has changed since mid-July, when four in 10 would have put their money on the line for Jeb Bush.
Overall: Republicans haven't had a very reliable crystal ball at their disposal before.
At this point in the last election, four in 10 Republicans thought Rick Perry was the likely candidate, and only 28 percent thought Mitt Romney.
The majority seem to find the Trump campaign persuasive.
Even if Republicans back another candidate, Trump will trump almost every other candidate.
Some experts think the divided camp is likely to benefit Trump as Trump's opponents split into supporters of different candidates.
A Monmouth University poll in early September revealed that in an imaginary duel between Trump and almost any other Republican candidate, Trump would almost always win over a larger base of supporters.
He leads Carly Fiorina with 13 points, Marco Rubio with 14 points, Walker with 15, Jeb Bush with 19 and Rand Paul, John Kasich and Chris Christie with 33 each.
With Ted Cruz, he's even.
Is Cruz Trump's only real opponent?
Ben Carson would trump Trump by 19 points in an imaginary duel.
A narrow majority of Trump supporters say they have already made a decision to vote.
According to a CBS/NYT poll released Tuesday, well over half of Trump supporters are confident in their voting decision.
Of course, the situation can change for a number of reasons, and at the moment a certain voter can also change his or her mind.
Forty-six percent of Trump supporters have not made a final decision.
Trump's toughest rival at the moment is neurosurgeon Ben Carson, but voters who have already chosen their candidate are twice as likely to vote for Trump.
Six in 10 Republicans agree with Trump's view on migration.
