Jeremy Corbyn's debut at Prime Minister's Question Time
After the election, Corbyn's first appearance at Prime Minister's Question Time has been eagerly awaited
Labour's new frontbencher Jeremy Corbyn is due to stand up for the first time to mingle his strength with David Cameron on Question Time later.
Mr Corbyn will ask the first of his six questions shortly after midday. The media and Labour figures will be watching the man with a hard eye.
Corbyn has called for less theater and more fact-finding for the weekly show.
He has also stated that he could skip some of the sessions and leave them to his colleagues.
The encounter will see Corbyn's leadership weighed in for the first time in the context. Corbyn will now face a parliamentary test following the assembly of the shadow cabinet and his speech to Corbyn's Trade Union Confederation (TUC) annual conference on Tuesday.
The decision by the Labour frontbencher to keep quiet during the 75th anniversary of the UK's air war during the national anthem on Tuesday has been criticised by a number of Tory party representatives. The silence has also made the front page headlines of several newspapers.
Corbyn's silence during the national anthem drew attention
Corbyn's representative noted that Corbyn stood during the national anthem, silently honoring the heroism of the Royal Air Force in the Battle of Britain.
But Owen Smith, a member of Corbyn's shadow cabinet, told the BBC's Two's Newsnight programme that he would have urged the party leader to join in the national anthem despite his opposition to the monarchy.
A dozen shadow ministers have refused to join Corbyn's first team, citing differences on economic, defence and foreign affairs. Fewer than a sixth of the party originally supported Corbyn's election to the party leadership.
BBC political correspondent Robin Brant thinks political differences over the UK's membership of the EU and the government's clampdown on benefits have been piling up in the Labour Party since Mr Corbyn's appointment.
Mr Corbyn told a TUC meeting that Labour would propose changes to remove restrictions altogether.
Hours later, Mr Smith, the shadow cabinet secretary for work and pensions, said the party's position was very clear: it was only opposed to the government's plans to reduce the limit from £26,000 to £23,000.
Mr Corbyn is the fifth Labour leader David Cameron will face in the past decade at the head of the Tory party.
The Labour leader, who has promised a new approach to politics, says he has chosen the questions to be put to Mr Cameron from the 30,000 proposals he has received from the public.
Mr Corbyn, who was elected in the Islington North constituency, says there are too many clashes on Question Time. Indeed, he promises to avoid clever diction and loan-throwing and says he will focus instead on serious topics such as poverty, inequality and the challenges facing young people.
Mr Corbyn has stated that shadow minister Angela Eagle fills in for him during Question Time, for example when Mr Cameron is on a trip abroad.
Mr Corbyn has also thrown into the air the idea that others could also get out loud at times. He says he has discussed the issue with John Bercow, the Speaker of the House of Commons.
After Corbyn took over the party leadership in 2005, Cameron stated that he wanted a puppeteer-like policy, often associated with Question Time. Some years later, however, he admitted that he had failed in his quest.
Since Question Time was first televised in 1990, it has been seen as a key measure of a leader's judgment, control of the House of Commons and position. But critics say Question Time has become a caricature in need of major reform.
