Pound strengthens as UK wages rise
The pound strengthened as wages rose in the UK, and SABMiller dragged the FTSE 100 index higher.
Between May and July, wages in the UK rose by 2.9 per cent compared with the same period last year. Bonuses were not included.
The faster-than-forecast growth was the fastest since 2009.
The pound strengthened by 1 per cent to $1.5505 against the euro and to €1.3730 against the euro.
The FTSE 100 index rose 1.49 per cent to end at 6,229.21 points.
The biggest riser was SABMiller, whose rate soared 20 per cent when the company received an initial takeover offer from rival firm AB InBev.
If completed, the deal would combine the world's two largest brewing companies and bring under one roof brands including Budweiser, Stella Artois, Peroni and Grolsch.
Burberry's stock rose 0.9 per cent in the wake of positive results from rival group Richemont, which focuses on luxury goods.
Richemont's latest sales figures are better than forecast. Sales momentum was also bullish in Burberry's key market of China.
Glencore's stock rose 5 per cent after the mining giant announced plans to raise $2.5bn through a share issue as part of its debt reduction strategy.
Shares in Mondi, the packaging and paper group, were the biggest faller with their 4.3 per cent drop as Goldman Sachs dropped the price of shares in the company for sale purposes.
JD Sports was up 3.1 per cent after the sports company announced that its pre-tax profit will rise 83 per cent to £46.6 million.
JD Sports boss says higher wage bills could hamper expansion
Peter Cowgill, executive chairman of JD Sports, said an increase in the minimum wage in the UK would mean more buying power for would-be customers.
However, the increased purchasing power is not sufficient to cover the higher labour costs for the company.
Mr Cowgill said rising labour costs could jeopardise JD Sports' expansion plans and reduce the need for more labour.
Metcash launches grassroots campaign against Aldi surge
Metcash is seeking to secure its IGA stores from a takeover by Aldi in South and Western Australia.
Food wholesaler Metcash has launched a grassroots campaign to maintain IGA retail market share in South and Western Australia against Aldi's 700 million Australian dollar invasion.
Aldi plans to open two distribution centres and the first of up to 120 stores in South and Western Australia early next year. Metcast and the IGA supermarkets will solidify their relationships with local food suppliers and build the IGA brand through marketing in mainstream media and social media, as well as hosting events such as the Adelaide show.
IGA stores and suppliers, as well as many brands, are involved in the campaign. For example, Simmo, an ice cream factory in Dunsborough, offers tastings in IGA stores, and merchants sell regular customers tickets to South Australian Football League games at discount prices.
Metcash is expected to announce more details of its defence strategy on September 29, when the food, alcohol and hardware wholesaler will hold its annual investment strategy day.
At issue is a significant market, with South and Western Australia making up almost 30 per cent of the footprint of Metcash's IGA stores, and these areas have a higher margin yield than the IGA store network in the eastern states.
South and West Australian consumers are known for being parochial, and indeed IGA retailers have a significantly higher market share in the region than NSW, Victoria and Queensland. South Australia has a market share of 30 per cent and Western Australia 24 per cent, while eastern states account for just 14 per cent.
Analysts at Morgan Stanley, for example, believe Aldi will grab 5 per cent of the food market in the two states within 12 months of the first stores opening. The chain is eating into sales from all operators, but especially from non-chain operators.
This week, Morgan Stanley analyst Tom Kierath estimated there could be a $360 million sell-off for IGA traders and a $250 million notch for Metcash by the end of 2016.
The forecast is based on the assumption that Aldi will open 25 stores in South and Western Australia next year and reach sales of between $500 million and $600 million in those areas.
Metcash's fixed costs are high, so the loss of food sales and volume could mean it losing $13 million in earnings before interest and tax, notes Kierath.
Meanwhile, Metcast is losing market share in eastern states mainly to Aldi and Coles, although recent research by Roy Morgan suggests IGA customers are the most loyal.
Morgan Stanley believes Metcash's food sales will fall 3.8 per cent in 2016, 4.1 per cent in 2017 and 2.1 per cent in 2018. Its market share would fall from 14 per cent in 2015 to 10.3 per cent by 2020.
Last week, Hamish Douglass, a leading portfolio manager at Magellan Financial Group, told an event in Melbourne that he thought it highly likely that Metcash would disappear completely within ten years.
Metcash has refused to take a public stance on Douglass' comments.
It is understood a member of the Metcash board contacted Douglass last week.
IGA's market share has dropped from 18 per cent to 14 per cent since 2010, and Metcash's food business, which serves 1,200 IGA dealers, has seen its earnings fall 43 per cent from 2012 levels. The figures show a reduction in debt financing as pressures hit sales and margins.
However, the wholesale operator is taking countermeasures and is making an annual investment of more than 150 million Australian dollars to match Coles and Woolworths prices on hundreds of products each week. The chain wants to support retailers in revamping stores to boost fresh produce offerings and improve the store's own-brand food range.
Metcash chief executive Ian Morrice says a review of prices and plans to revamp stores are well under way, with the company able to increase profits again in 2017 for the first time in four years.
Australian Tennis Association president Steve Healy defends Thanasi Kokkinakis
Thanasi Kokkinakis deserves special mention for his behaviour rather than criticism.
According to Australian Tennis Federation president Steve Healy, Thanasi Kokkinakis has been a collateral damage in the recent Nick Kyrgios-related yupaka. Kokkinakis deserves special mention in lieu of criticism.
Kokkinakis, the younger side of the duo named "Special K," was thrust into an unfavourable spotlight when bad boy Kyrgios provoked his opponent Stan Wawrinka at the ATP tournament in Montreal.
Shortly thereafter, in a qualifying game between Kokkinakis and Ryan Harrison in Cincinnati, the umpire twice had to separate the rivals. "Wawrinka should have given a beating to Kyrgiosis and me for that guy," Harrison noted.
At the U.S. Open, Kokkinakis hit the court with a bat in frustration as strong cramps marred his match. Healy has faithfully defended Kokkinakis.
Currently the teenage star is in Glasgow where he will battle with Sam Groth for the singles second spot behind Bernard Tomic in the Davis Cup semi-final against Great Britain.
"I feel strongly that Thanasi has been dragged into the controversy," Healy said.
"He broke a racket when he lost a match at the U.S. Open. He is by no means the first player to break his racket out of frustration. I know Thanas well enough that he is not proud of what he has done.
But he has endured very well, for example, Harrison's provocative behavior at the U.S. Open, and I think he deserves recognition.
He's got a strong team and a great family around him and I just think he's been treated a little bit unfairly.
He is very mature for 19, he works hard and complements the team well. He has never had any problems with other players, and he is respected among the players. He trains hard, is in good condition and is a really stable and mature young man. I feel he should be judged on his own merits."
Healy also backed the decision to drop Kyrgios from the Australian squad for the all-important round that starts on Friday. Healy describes the solution as a joint decision that works for all parties. However, he is in favour of the Canberra-raised returning as a long-term endorsement of the team.
"First and foremost, we want to focus fully on the matches rather than the polemic surrounding Kyrgios," stated Healy.
Nick has come out on top quickly. As Federer and Murray, among others, have pointed out, the youngster will have to grow up in the public spotlight. He deserves the criticism he has received for his bad mistakes. However, we will try to support him to understand the consequences of his actions. We will also try to provide him with some privacy. I believe it is best for both the whole team and Nick."
