The turmoil on Hungary's border with Serbia began a day later when the 28-nation bloc failed in attempts to develop a common migration policy at a contentious meeting in Brussels.
But the ministers agreed that responsibility for the 40,000 influx of asylum seekers in Italy and Greece is shared. The meeting raised hopes that an agreement could be reached by next month or the end of the year on which EU member states would take in 120,000 migrants, including from Hungary.
German Chancellor Angela Merkel and Austria called an extraordinary summit for the next week on Tuesday to discuss the migrant crisis on the continent.
But Hungary was not pinning its hopes on swift action by Brussels or neighbouring countries.
On Tuesday, the emergency situation developed so that the authorities in the two southern regions were allowed to adopt more effective measures, namely closing roads and speeding up legal procedures in the area of asylum.
