CBS News correspondent Charlie D'Agata reports that even prisoners took part in the bidding process for the job of finishing the barbed wire fences between Hungary and Serbia.
In recent months, Hungary has become a clear bottleneck for migrants and a transit point to the European Union. Many of these migrants are refugees from Syria and other parts of the Middle East.
But Prime Minister Viktor Orban argued that most of the people arriving are standard of living refugees, not war refugees with the right to seek refuge. The view diverges sharply from those of other EU states, including Germany.
Under the new law, which came into force at midnight in Hungary, it is an offence to cross or damage a four-metre high barbed wire fence the government has built on the southern border in the direction of Serbia. The law also specifies longer prison terms for convicted traffickers.
"Because of the situation caused by the mass migration, the government is declaring a state of crisis in the country," government spokesman Zoltan Kovacs told reporters in the town of Szeged in the south of the country.
"We are taking a hard line: illegal border crossing is a crime."
In practice, parliament still has to approve military action, which is expected next week. Associated Press news agency reporters along the border have for several days seen heavily armed soldiers with vehicles and military dogs.
Orban's internal security adviser, Gyorgy Bakondi, said authorities had apprehended 45 people trying to cross the border immediately at the border and 15 further afield.
People who have been able to cross the border by damaging the fence are now being held by the police, charged with crimes under new laws.
Authorities are quickly mending the fence.
In addition, Hungarian authorities closed two of the seven border crossings on the Serbian border on Tuesday. One border crossing was closed using a train car covered in barbed wire.
Chaos engulfed the main border crossing near Roszke, Hungary, as Hungarians opened an access point in a small metal container where people packed in.
