Here's how the U.S. Federal Reserve's (Fed's) interest rate hike will affect
Rising interest rates and a boom in the stock market are souring, securities yields are rising and the economy is sliding into a depression.
We know that.
We don’t know how long it will take and how long the effects will last.
In the case of the economy, in particular, we find hints of timing in history.
The recession has arrived in up to 11 months since the first interest rate hike and lasted up to 86 months.
The central bank often aggressively raises interest rates, though not always. The determining factor is how the economy and financial assets respond.
That's why central bank officials have already been vehemently stressing that investors would pay attention not to when interest rates start to rise but to how long it will take for the situation to normalize.
There are, of course, several variables involved.
Ultimately, though, market participants may find that any fuss about raising interest rates may be overblown.
"The central bank's first withdrawal since the global financial crisis was no doubt often interpreted as a sign of the end of cheap money," Julian Jessop, chief global economist at Capital Economics, told clients.
On the other hand, we do not expect a gradual normalisation of interest rates to fairly low levels, which is a frightening seismic shock for many.
But that doesn't mean there won't be an impact.
Here are examples, based on historical trends, of how the effects can be seen in different areas of the economy:
As the market has seen for about a month now, the portent of raising interest rates could add to volatility for a while.
When interest rates finally rise, the effect won't be so dramatic.
"The trend appears to be for capital yields to stagnate after the first drawdown for 12 to 24 months, perhaps reflecting yet another lag in monetary policy, a Deutsche Bank analyst noted in a recent study of the consequences of rising interest rates.
Adjusted over 35 years, the market usually sees a sharp rise in interest rates at the time of the rise, around 14 per cent, fairly flat for the next 250 days (an average rise of 2.6 per cent), after 500 days the situation normalises, and the average yield on fixed income after six share cycles is 14.4 per cent, according to Bob Doll, chief equity strategist at Nuveen Asset Management in Barron's.
Deutsche said the impact on equities tends to intensify a little later in the cycle and fixed income starts to decline.
The recession is a fact of life in the economy, but rising interest rates tend to do the trick.
In this case, if the central bank faces conditions that didn't exist before and could spur a downturn.
It is particularly noteworthy that GDP is at its lowest level ever for a central bank rate hike.
According to Deutsche Bank, in 118 policy rate hikes since 1950, only twice has the face value been below 4.5 per cent.
While the second quarter of 2015 shows 3.6 percent, not many imagined it would last, and the third quarter is at 1.5 percent, according to the Atlanta Regional Federal Reserve.
Raising interest rates in such a sensitive economic climate can have its risks and one can ask whether this situation is different," Deutsche said.
Market participants have been talking about raising the key interest rate all year, and eyes will turn to this week's Federal Open Market Committee meeting, which ends on Thursday.
Many strategists and economists believe that even if the Open Market Committee approves the drawdown at this meeting, futures trading will show only a 25 percent probability.
"In our studies, from 1950 all withdrawal cycles up to today have been in a supercycle, with GDP, which was also falling before the downturn, rising very rapidly after the start of the boom," it said.
The recovery has been extremely slow compared to the worst recession of the control period.
The cycle is clearly the longest the Federal Reserve has been waiting since the last recession. The record had been 35 months, now it is already the 74th month.
Fixed income securities have also been volatile as the market heralds a rate hike, and the pattern is also repeated on the capital side.
"The fundamental difference is that the impact is faster in bonds than in equities when the central bank changes course.
For bonds, the yield seems to change direction immediately as the first up/down cycle kicks in.
At the end of the bullish cycle, yields will fall immediately," Deutsche noted.
Strategists at Charles Schwab believe the rate hike will cause long- and short-term bonds to approach each other and flatten the curve.
"High-yield bonds often do better in this kind of environment, although we're still cautious about yields," said Kathy Jones, a fixed-income securities analyst at Schwab.
Intriguingly, Mr Jones says the market has already adapted to the central bank's upcoming change in direction.
"Beyond dollar appreciation and inflation forecasts, we are already seeing a number of signs of adjustment to tighter financial policy," Jones says.
Short-term interest rates are rising, the yield curve is straight, credit risk spreads have widened and volatility has increased. All are typical of markets in a situation where the central bank is tightening policy.
Broadly speaking, companies that operate mainly in the U.S. market are benefiting because interest rates are falling and local products are starting to attract.
The outlook for indebted multinationals is weaker, as a strengthening dollar causes their products to become more expensive in global markets and debt to become more expensive.
"History shows that quality stocks will be more lucrative in the three months following a rate hike," Goldman Sachs analysts tell their clients.
Companies with strong balance sheets outperformed companies with weak balance sheets after rate increases in 1994, 1999 and 2004 by an average of five percentage points.
Companies with high return on capital, as well as low volatility stocks, also fared better in quality, averaging 4 and 3 percentage points respectively.
"The debt is a big question.
Companies with a significant share of variable-rate debt stand to lose the most," Goldman noted.
Outside the stock market, consumers also tend to benefit from the dollar's strengthening.
Savers will also benefit thanks to higher returns. Experts are, admittedly, divided on how quickly the effects will be seen.
