Nematodes do not normally respond to ultrasound. However, Chalasani noticed that the worms begin to react when placed in a liquid with microscopic bubbles.
Chalasan says the bubbles intensify ultrasound waves that propagate inside the worms.
Augmented ultrasound waves affect TRP4 ion channels that are present in some of the worms' cell membranes.
According to a paper published in Nature Communications, sound waves cause these ion channels to open and activate the cells they are attached to.
In order to control nematodes by ultrasound, Chalasani genetically modified the worms so that some of the nerves controlling their movement appeared TRP4 ion channels.
When ultrasound was directed at the modified worms, the microbubbles amplified sound waves and migrated to the worms, setting off a signal in the nerve cell.
The method is a bit like optogenetics, a revolutionary tool that allows scientists to activate nerve cells using light.
However, according to Chalasan, sonogenetics has certain advantages over optogenetics.
Light is light directed to the brain under study using optical fibers. Low-frequency ultrasounds, on the other hand, penetrate the cell easily, so ultrasound can be directed to the brain through the skull.
"We believe that with gene therapy and viral therapy, human nerve cells can be momentarily exposed to ultrasound signals in a clinical setting for certain neurological treatments," concluded Chalasani.
According to the researcher, the method could also be utilized in muscle cells and insulin-producing cells.
