The most important lessons I can sum up in eight simple rules.
Moving into a dormitory is at its mildest a strenuous experience and at its worst a shocking one.
It's easy to get rambling in the situation: you tell everyone what you're about, whether you took a gap year and why, how you like Corbyn and why you don't "actually hate or love Marmite, because that's just yeast extract, hahaha, I'm in my room."
Take a breath sometimes.
And help others breathe: show your interest and ask other people questions.
Asking questions will guide the conversation and help you find the people you like and the people you wouldn't talk to even when your lashes were flaring up and these people were handing out fire extinguishers.
Give others space.
Private rooms often serve as drinking counters, movie theaters and public lounges, but a private room is also a place to dress up, starting with your underwear.
