Eurozone inflation eases to 0.1% in August
Consumer prices in the eurozone rose only marginally, or 0.1 per cent year-on-year, in August, Eurostat, the EU's statistical authority, said today.
The rise in prices was dragged down by lower energy prices.
Eurostat thus revised down its preliminary estimate of 0.2% a couple of weeks ago.
In July, the rate of inflation was 0.2 percent.
So-called core inflation fell to 0.9 percent in August from 1.0 percent in July.
Eurostat's preliminary estimate of core inflation was 1.0 per cent.
Energy was 7.2 per cent cheaper in the eurozone last month than a year ago.
Across the 28-nation EU as a whole, the average inflation rate was zero in August.
July saw a 0.1 percent rise.
Of the euro area countries, consumer prices rose most, by 1.4 per cent, in August in Malta.
In Cyprus, inflation was lowest with prices falling by 1.9 per cent.
In Finland, inflation was 0.2 per cent negative according to the EU Harmonised Price Index.
Inflation in the euro area remains persistently far from the European Central Bank's (ECB) target of a price rise of around 2 per cent over the medium term.
The ECB is forecasting an average inflation rate of 0.1% for the eurozone for this year.
Next year, the rise will pick up to 1.1 percent, the central bank anticipated in its new inflation forecasts released in early September.
U.S. Fed next tries to tighten monetary policy
The next U.S. recession will begin at its fastest pace in less than a year, but with more certainty within three years after the country's central bank, the Fed, steps in to raise its interest rates again.
And in financial markets, meanwhile, the downgrade will begin before the next recession.
The Fed has hinted at possibly starting rate hikes as early as this week and by the end of the year at the latest.
This means that the next recession could hit us at its fastest by next autumn and the course of the financial markets before that.
Or at least that will be the case if the world's largest economy and financial markets perform as they have been wont to do - and if they react to the Fed's monetary taps tightening as they have in the past.
Such conclusions have been reached by Jim Reid, Nick Burns and Seb Barker, strategists at Deutsche Bank London market research, in their extensive study of long-term market and economic cycles.
The bank distributed the more than 60-page Long-Term Asset Return Study to its major international clients last week.
The strategists who produced the study and the report don't pretend to know when exactly the Fed will move to raise its interest rates or what will happen in the economy and markets after that.
Instead, they present economic statistics using cool facts and their calculations of how the economy and markets have behaved in the past at the time of and after the Fed's rate hikes.
In addition to historical observations, they will look at what key variables in the economy and financial markets are now on the same or another pattern as at the time of previous rate increases - and what might come of it.
It becomes clear that both the economy and the financial markets are now in shakier shape to withstand rising interest rates than at any time since the 1950s.
Maybe not a year into the recession.
Throughout last summer and early autumn, leaders deciding on the Fed's monetary policy and its respective stance have hinted that the time is beginning to be ripe for raising interest rates.
The first interest rate hike in more than nine years could come as soon as this week.
The issue will be resolved over the course of Wednesday and Thursday when the Fed's board's so-called open market committee meets to decide at its two-day meeting.
The last time the Fed raised its so-called Fed funds policy rate was in June 2006.
That was the end of exactly two years of relatively regular but at a time small 0.25 percentage point rate hikes by the Fed to raise its interest rate from 1.25 percent to 5.25 percent.
The financial market's symptoms began in 2007 with the difficulties of the riskiest U.S. housing finance, and a year later the financial crisis tore into a global doomsday nightmare.
The Great Recession came in 2009.
Last time around, the severe adversity in financial markets and the real economy began at a slower pace than has typically been the case since previous Fed rate hikes.
Similarly, the trials were then tougher and harsher than at any time since the Depression of the 1930s.
Deutsche's strategists have sifted through the ups and downs of the world's largest economies and the twists and turns of financial markets since 1950 and, in some places, since the early 19th century.
They make sense of the Fed's rate hikes and their economic and fiscal impact since the 1950s.
It has been less than a year since the first rate hike, usually less than three years and less than three and a half years on average.
The rise in financial markets has ended within a year-two of the Fed's rate hikes starting.
The Fed has alternately raised and lowered its key interest rate since the early 1950s by a dozen cycles of varying lengths.
Each time has differed from the others in some respects, and the narrator is relatively sparse in the examination, so it is hardly possible to conclude anything certain about the effects of subsequent rate increases.
The strategists remind us that this time around, many things are different.
And not only better.
Interest rates too low for too long
The crucial causes of the financial crisis, let alone the culprits, may not be conclusively identified even by decades of research.
But three things about the causes that led to the crisis and increased its destructive power are probably somewhat indisputably clear:
1) In the 2000s, the Fed, the eurozone ECB and other major central banks in the world kept their key interest rates too low for too long.
They patched up the marks of the tech bubble, while growing the next one.
2) The amount of debt accumulated in different parts of the financial and real economy over the decades, and which was already too high, became even greater due to the over-loose monetary policy of central banks.
It was the largest debt bubble in history.
3) In particular, the crazy cheap debt financing that packed into the financial economy almost without restraint swelled the biggest exchange rate bubbles in most parts of the financial markets to date, from equities to real estate, bonds and commodities.
Nor is it likely to generate very severe controversy that financial markets, which have soared to heights on increasingly convoluted leverage, were in an unusually dangerous and volatile spot the last time the Fed and other central banks drove up interest rates.
Financial structures rigged with debt levers, let alone valuation bubbles, did not last more than their time after rate hikes had begun and the cost of debt financing had turned upwards.
The risks materialized as a financial crisis, followed by the Great Recession.
Bigger bubble and more debt
Deutsche’s strategists do not speculate on what will happen next, but they do give some reason to wonder, for example by mentioning the following:
1) The Fed and other major central banks have now kept their monetary policy stance even lighter for even longer than before the financial crisis.
If interest rates were too low for too long before the crisis, they have now been even lower for even longer.
2) Debt has not been cheap for a long time as it was ten years ago, but now debt money is literally cheaper than free money.
Thus, the debt load of the financial and real economies has not eased, but now there is a much heavier debt load in different parts of the economy than before the financial crisis or at any time before it.
3) More liquid and cheaper than before, central bank liquidity has largely remained in the financial markets and has curbed key securities and assets to their most expensive levels since the pre-financial crisis peak or at any time.
And not only are strategists flattening the mood with warning signs from financial markets, they also point out that even the U.S. economy has yet to recover from the financial crisis and the heaviest recession in decades to the pattern that has transpired in the past.
The eurozone economy has barely recovered at all.
The real economy, in other words, is in unusually weak shape but correspondingly the pressures and risks in financial markets are incomparably greater than they were before the financial crisis, when the Fed next moves to tighten its monetary taps tighter.
Perhaps the picture of the future of Albert Edwards, strategist at Societe Generale, the French bank, is not as strange as it may seem.
For a good while, he has been grooming the bank's international investor clients for the Fed's following turnarounds:
First the Fed raises interest rates, then the financial bubbles burst - and soon it will be time for the Fed to race to put out the financial fires with even bigger QE money syringes.
