This week, policymakers at the Federal Reserve are gathering for the most anticipated meeting in years. A crowd sits down at an eight-foot-diameter Honduran wooden table to decide whether it's time to raise interest rates for the first time in nearly a decade.
On the wall of the central bank's ornate, two-story conference room stands a mural of the United States.
The map is a reminder that Federal Reserve Speaker Janet L. Yellen and her colleagues must put the state's economic interest above all other interests.
The central bank has a double provision from Congress: maximize employment in the United States and keep prices stable here.
Since the Great Depression, however, the central bank's leadership has noted a third unwritten mandate: economic stability.
That mandate could be the missing piece of a tortuous decision. On Thursday, the central bank is due to announce whether the U.S. economy is ready to begin weaning off the unforeseen stimulus provided by short-term interest rates that stayed near zero from late 2008.
While most of the data shows the economy is growing solidly, the recent turmoil in financial markets may have officials at the already cautious Federal Reserve spooked into adding to the volatility by raising the benchmark federal tax rate – even by a percentage point in a quarter.
"The labor market and inflation are obviously first and foremost in their hands-on monitoring," said Lindsey M. Piegza, chief economist at the banking firm Stifel Nicolaus & Co.
"However, I believe that if the central bank is looking for an excuse not to raise taxes, the increased uncertainty in global markets is enough to warrant a further wait," Piegza continues.
Those who have thought about it don't agree on what the central bank is up to, which in itself is causing nervousness.
About half of economists surveyed by Bloomberg fumed about rising interest rates this week.
But financial markets think the central bank is waiting, with only a 30 per cent chance of a drawdown, according to the key indicator.
If the central bank raises its key interest rate, stock prices could fall unless policymakers soften the blow by promising another drawdown.
On Tuesday, the Dow Jones industrial average leapt 228.89 points or 1.4 percentage points to 16,599.85.
"The glimmer was driven by expectations that the central bank will hold a key interest rate steady this week," said John Lonski, chief economist at Moody's Capital Markets Research Group.
"It would be a surprise if the central bank were to raise the rate at this point," he noted.
"If that were to happen, the central bank would have to think carefully about how to keep the hands of those operating in the financial markets from shaking."
Experts on the other, meanwhile, noted that raising interest rates could calm financial markets and remove uncertainty about when the central bank will act.
Just a month ago, the central bank appeared to be leaning toward raising interest rates by 0.25 percentage points this month. It would be the first small step in tightening financing conditions and, by extension, bolstering the U.S. recovery.
Throughout the spring and early summer, Yellen has stated that she expected to raise interest rates this year – despite the fact that liberals say economic progress is needed.
Although job creation slowed in August, labor market growth has been solid this year.
The unemployment rate fell to 5.1% last month. Its level is now at its lowest level in seven years and close to the level the central bank puts at full employment.
Payrolls look to pick up
While inflation continued to fall below the central bank's annual 2 percent targets, central bank policymakers noted that a key reason for this is the sharp temporary impact on oil prices.
"The economy can make do with higher interest rates and it needs them as long as they take into account the tight situation in the labour market," said Ian Shepherdson, chief economist at Pantheon Macroeconomics.
But financial markets around the world were not startled last month when China devalued its currency.
The Dow Jones industrial average tumbled as much as 16 percentage points from May's record high and investors feared China's economic decline would also affect global growth.
The market has picked up this month, and the Dow Jones is now down nearly 10 percent since peaking in May.
The turmoil in the markets means that central bank policymakers are getting even more complicated in their consideration of a key interest rate hike.
"The central bank's work is getting more complicated, despite what happened in the financial markets and the news that has come out about the deterioration of the Chinese economy in recent weeks," Stephen D. Oliner, a senior researcher at the UCLA Ziman Center for Real Estate and a former central bank official, noted.
Now he believes the central bank will wait at least a month to be able to deal with the impact.
"There is great uncertainty about what will be the impact on the US economy. There is little reliable data on the situation following the recent development of the Chinese economy," Oliner noted.
Restoring the global economy is not the central bank's main concern, so in principle it should not influence the central bank's decision-making.
In practice, however, the central bank is the world's most influential monetary body.
The central bank's influence in recent years has been enormous.
In 2013, the mere suggestion by then-Chairman Ben S. Bernanken that the central bank could narrow the scope of its operations prompted upheaval around the world.
In today's world, markets and economies are closely intertwined. In addition to monitoring world developments, the central bank is also required to engage with other central banks and experts to have a good overall picture of the global economy.
"The central bank's decision-making process is more art than science," Zachary Karabell, senior vice president for global strategy at fund management firm Envestnet Inc., noted.
Chairman Jeffrey Lacker of the Richmond Regional Central Bank noted this month that the central bank has in the past overreacted to moves in financial markets that don't seem to have a connection to the fundamental pillars of the economy.
Lacker, a voting member of the Federal Open Market Committee, has called for raising the key interest rate, citing the 1998 and 1999 decisions as an example.
"The Asian financial crisis led the central bank to decide at three meetings to cut the key interest rate by 0.75 percentage points, despite the limited availability of identifiable sanctions for economic growth in the United States," Lacker told me.
A year later, the central bank reversed that decision.
"The central bank should put monetary stability first only in a significant crisis, such as the 2008 financial meltdown," said Adam S. Posen, a former member of the Bank of England's interest rate-setting committee.
The latest turmoil doesn't even approximate the situation at the time," he said.
"There is absolutely no reason to fear an interest rate hike because of market shocks," Posen, of the Peterson Institute for International Economics, added.
"The Federal Reserve Act still has a dual mandate and makes no mention of monetary stability. Until there is a change to this, I don't think we should get ahead of ourselves."
