Mildly overweight diabetics may benefit from obesity surgery
According to a new study, mildly overweight type 2 diabetics may benefit from obesity surgery for at least five years.
However, it is too early to say whether mildly overweight type 2 diabetics will live longer after obesity surgery than those who receive unresectable treatment.
"It takes time to get mortality data," said Dr. Robin Blackstone, an expert in obesity surgery who covered the new study in the journal JAMA Surgery.
Obesity surgery, or bariatric surgery, reduces the stomach by various methods.
Surgical methods reduce the feeling of hunger and limit the absorption of food in the body.
Over the years, bariatric surgery has been found to be an effective treatment for type 2 diabetes. However, the majority of studies have involved morbidly overweight individuals with a body mass index (BMI) of at least 35.
Body mass index indicates weight and height, where the normal value is between 18.5 and 24.9.
When the BMI is over 25, the person is overweight, and a BMI above 30 indicates significant obesity.
You can calculate your own BMI at 1.usa.gov/1D0ZqDv.
In the new study, researchers at Min-Sheng Hospital in Taiwan utilized data collected since 2007 in a study comparing two methods of obesity surgery, gastric bypass and sleeve surgery, with drug treatments for type 2 diabetes in mildly obese individuals.
After obesity surgery, the average BMI dropped from 31 to 24.5 by the end of the fifth year of the study.
Body mass index in the non-operative treatment group was maintained around 29.
For those who underwent surgery, diabetes was completely cured at 36 percent and partially cured at 28 percent.
In the drug-treated group, diabetes was completely cured in only 1 percent and partially cured in only about 2 percent.
The study also found blood pressure, triglycerides and bad LDL cholesterol were better in the surgically treated group.
The researchers also monitored patients' hemoglobin A1c levels, which describes the development of blood sugar levels.
Researchers say the recommended level of hemoglobin-A1c is less than 7 percent.
After surgery, hemoglobin-A1c levels dropped from an average of 9 percent to 6 percent.
In the drug-treated group, the value remained unchanged at about 8 percent.
A hemoglobin-A1c count indicates control of blood sugar levels. However, a team led by Dr Chih-Cheng Hsu found that this did not reduce mortality over five years.
The team also compared the consequences of two different surgery methods.
In the fifth year in the gastric bypass group, weight loss was greater compared to the sleeve surgery group (18.7 and 14.2 kg), body mass index drop was greater (7.4 and 5.1), as were hemoglobin-A1c levels (3.1 percent and 2.1 percent). In the bypass group, diabetes was also completely cured by a larger proportion (46.9 percent and 16.7 percent, respectively).
The new study failed to show a lower death rate after five years. However, according to a Swedish study by Blackstone, who works at the University of Arizona College of Medicine in Phoenix, surgical treatment brings years of life for obese individuals.
In a Swedish study, obese people who underwent gastric bypass surgery had a 29 percent reduction in the odds of death over 15 years compared to the group who received traditional treatment.
While the new study found no lower mortality, Blackstone said there was confirmation that individuals with a body mass index below 35 could benefit from the procedure.
"This is the main finding of the study, which concludes that surgery is safe in the lower body mass index group and does not increase the risk of death or kidney disease," Blackstone wrote.
Blackstone said people and doctors should take weight seriously when the BMI is between 27 and 30.
"We wait too long for people to start taking the situation seriously," the researcher concluded.
"When you've accumulated genetic changes in a person's body that predispose them to obesity and diabetes, it's really hard to turn the situation around."
