Cases of hand swallowing quadruple in children in four years
According to the Georgia Poison Control Center, poison control centers across the U.S. report a nearly fourfold increase in cases of ingestion of hand sanitizer, which is high in alcohol content, in children under 12 since 2010.
According to Gaylord Lopez, director of the Georgia Poison Control Center, cases of ingestion of hand sanitizer reported to poison control centers in children under the age of 12 increased from 3,266 in 2010 to 16,117 in 2014.
"These products are increasingly out of the reach of children, and unfortunately, some children are being put in emergency rooms," Lopez told CNN.
Lopez said children drink hand sanitizer intentionally, some to impress their friends and some prompted by social media.
YouTube videos feature teenagers drinking disinfectant for cheap hops.
Teens are reportedly mixing alcohol mouthwash with disinfectant to make the drink even stronger.
Younger children may be tempted by the smell of hand sanitizer.
"The kid doesn't think the stuff is bad," Lopez said.
"A lot of attractive hand sanitizer products are freshly perfumed.
There are hand sanitizers with strawberry, grape and orange flavors to appeal to kids."
The alcohol content of disinfectants is 45-95%.
For young children, even a small amount can cause alcohol poisoning.
"The alcohol content in Handsides is very high," Dr. Stephen Thornton, medical director of the Poison Control Center at the University Hospital of Kansas, told Fox 4 in Kansas City.
"No one would leave a whisky shot within reach of children, but if hand sanitiser products are often left within reach of children, you can quickly get a large amount of alcohol out of them."
Six-year-old Nhaijah Russell recently enjoyed four loaves of strawberry-scented hand sanitizer at school, and the girl was delivered to the emergency room for treatment.
"The girl's blood alcohol level was 179, which is twice the adult hops limit," said Dr. Chris Ritchey of Gwinnett Medical Center near Atlanta, who treated the girl.
Nhaijah soured and couldn't walk when she was brought to the emergency room.
Doctors monitored the girl's condition overnight at a separate children's hospital for brain damage, as the girl had fallen and hit her head after consuming alcohol," Ritchey said.
"It was a really scary situation," Nhaijah's mother, Ortoria Scott, said on CNN.
My daughter could have died.
Lopez has recommended parents and teachers to use non-alcoholic products and disinfectant wipes in addition to moving your hand sanitizer out of reach of children.
In addition to alcohol poisoning, some disinfectants have been linked to deaths.
In 2013, two Ontario women died after swallowing hand sanitizer containing an unreported toxic substance.
Health officials thought the product contained the deadly methanol instead of ethyl alcohol, although the latter is listed as an active ingredient in the product label.
According to a police report, three fourth-graders in upstate New York planned to kill the "nasty" teacher in January by placing antibacterial products around the classroom.
The teacher is highly allergic to hand sanitizer and denied bringing it into the classroom.
Police ruled that the botched scheme was irrelevant and urged disciplinary action by the school.
