White House confirms Xi Jinping's Washington visit
A White House communique released Tuesday confirms that Chinese President Xi Jinping will travel to the United States on a state visit at the end of the month.
Xi Jinping arrives for his first official visit to Washington on September 25. It is a counter-visit after President Barack Obama visited Beijing last November.
Following bilateral talks between the heads of state, the US president and First Lady Michelle Obama will host a dinner for Xi Jinping and his wife Peng Liyuan to mark the state visit.
"President Xi Jinping's visit will provide an opportunity to expand U.S.-China cooperation on a wide range of global, regional and bilateral topics of mutual interest. At the same time, President Barack Obama and President Xi Jinping will have the opportunity for constructive discussions on topics on which there is disagreement," the White House communique states.
Xi Jinping's visit was first announced in February and he is expected to pop into Seattle to meet with several US tech leaders. From Seattle, the president's trip would go first to Washington and then to New York for the UN General Assembly on September 28.
Obama and Xi are expected to raise a range of controversial topics, including Washington's concerns about China's alleged cyber espionage and the country's increased activities in disputed waters in the South China Sea.
Matt Damon downplays diversity in filmmaking
Matt Damon had a heated chat with Effie Brown, an African-American, and noted that diversity was not needed behind the camera.
In an episode of HBO's Project Greenlight that aired on Sunday night, the seasoned actor interrupted Brown as he explained the importance of considering different views of the dark-skinned protagonist of the script chosen for the project.
"Diversity is considered in the casting of a movie, not in the casting of a program," Damon argued.
Brown gushed with dismay and hurt at the claim. "Wow, okay that," the woman noted after Damon's comment, which starred in "Alone on Mars."
Damon and Brown, along with fellow producers Ben Affleck and the Farrelly brothers, had gathered to discuss the race's finalists.
"Whoever is the director, I'd like to encourage you to think about how the character of Harmony is portrayed," Brown noted at first.
"The only dark-skinned character is a prostitute who has sex with her white pimp."
The producer of Dear White People endorsed Leo Angelos and Kristen Brancaccio to direct the film. Damon responded harshly that the duo's choice could lead to an unwanted outcome.
When the debate aired on television, social media exploded with Damon's disapproving comments.
Twitter user MrPooni expressed his anger at the scene in blunt terms: "The fact that Matt Damon is talking over the only dark-skinned person to explain what diversity is is so white-skinned it hurts."
The tweet was shared more than 5,000 times, and liked 4,000 times.
