Xi urges opening up economy to rest of world
"The economic system must open up to the rest of the world to promote growth," President Xi Jinping said Tuesday at a meeting of the Economic Reform Steering Group on Tuesday.
"China should commit to attracting foreign investment and expertise and develop a policy of economic opening," the president noted at the 16th meeting of the Central Leadership Group set up to deepen comprehensive reform.
"By advancing the policy of opening up and deepening reforms, a new impetus and vitality for economic growth will be injected," Xi noted.
The executive approved guidelines including a negative list to regulate market access, relaxing border control policies, promoting the inclusion of private capital in state-owned enterprises, and a review of the citizen registration system.
According to the Communication, a negative list of sectors and undertakings in which investment is prohibited will be drawn up.
The system is being gradually tested and is being developed through test programmes.
According to the Communication, this is a significant change, as it gives the market a greater role in resource allocation, the legal business environment and market opening.
The Government will also relax the supervision of companies, thus ensuring that companies have decision-making power over their own business.
According to the communiqué, China will allow the development of new models of cross-border cooperation in border regions, as well as the search for new mechanisms to promote regional growth.
With the opening up of government-controlled sectors, many industries are opening up to private investment.
"The government will not change its foreign investment policy. It will support the legitimate interests of companies that have received foreign funding and provide them with better services," the communique states.
In addition, applying for a permanent residence permit by optimizing requirements and streamlining the application process.
The meeting also touched upon the rights of lawyers to practice and the support of judges and prosecutors.
Premier Li Keqiang and party leaders Liu Yunshan and Zhang Gaoli also attended the meeting.
